Not always. I did quite a lot of Salesforce development, and their user interfaces were earlier written in ‘Visualforce’ like this, similar to what early Java servers did too.
```&lt;apex:page standardController="Contact" &gt;
    &lt;apex:form &gt;
        &lt;apex:pageBlock title="Edit Contact"&gt;
            &lt;apex:pageBlockSection columns="1"&gt;
                &lt;apex:inputField value="{!Contact.FirstName}"/&gt;
                &lt;apex:inputField value="{!Contact.LastName}"/&gt;
                &lt;apex:inputField value="{!Contact.Email}"/&gt;
                &lt;apex:inputField value="{!Contact.Birthdate}"/&gt;
            &lt;/apex:pageBlockSection&gt;
            &lt;apex:pageBlockButtons &gt;
                &lt;apex:commandButton action="{!save}" value="Save"/&gt;
            &lt;/apex:pageBlockButtons&gt;
        &lt;/apex:pageBlock&gt;
    &lt;/apex:form&gt;
&lt;/apex:page&gt;```
You could have Javascript, but it was uploaded to the server as a ‘resource’ with a name, totally separately.
Now skipping one UI framework that was used for some years (Aura Components), the new UI (Lightning Web Components) are written in standard formats.
In three files, HTML
```&lt;template&gt;
    &lt;input value={message}&gt;&lt;/input&gt;
&lt;/template&gt;```
Javascript
```import { LightningElement } from 'lwc';
export default class App extends LightningElement {
  message = 'Hello World';
}```
CSS
```input {
   color: blue;
}```
I would expect that most organisations using it have some mixture of the three in use. And yes, these are random examples I copied from Trailhead.

